=== #41 Scale and performance testing: Keycloak and Thundermail
## Objective

Establish baseline performance metrics and identify scaling limits for Keycloak (OIDC provider) and Thundermail (Stalwart mail service) before user growth makes testing under load impractical.

## Context

Both services have known scaling concerns documented in architecture reviews:

- **Keycloak** ([Accounts & Keycloak Architecture](docs/accounts-keycloak-architecture.md#scaling-assessment)): single point of failure for all authentication, low auto-scaling ceiling (max 4 tasks), Redis without Multi-AZ, no connection pooling, session storage in PostgreSQL
- **Thundermail** ([Thundermail Architecture](docs/thundermail-architecture.md#architecture-review-scaling-assessment)): PostgreSQL data store bottleneck, 2 mail nodes (t3a.large), no PROXY protocol, no auto-scaling, single-region deployment
- Related: #14 (security epic), #40 (accounts/keycloak security hardening)

## Keycloak Performance Testing

### Baseline Metrics to Establish
- [ ] Login flow latency (P50, P95, P99) under normal load
- [ ] Token refresh latency
- [ ] Max concurrent authentication sessions before degradation
- [ ] Database connection count under load
- [ ] Infinispan/JGroups cluster sync overhead with 2 vs 4 nodes

### Load Scenarios
- [ ] Sustained auth load: simulate N concurrent users cycling login → token refresh → logout
- [ ] Spike test: 10x normal auth rate for 5 minutes (simulates product launch or media coverage)
- [ ] Celery backpressure: high volume of async tasks (email verification, Stalwart provisioning) with constrained worker pool
- [ ] Node failure: kill one Keycloak task under load, measure recovery time and impact

### Tooling
- [k6](https://k6.io/) or [Locust](https://locust.io/) against the staging environment
- CloudWatch metrics for ECS task CPU/memory, RDS connections, Redis memory/connections
- Keycloak metrics endpoint (`/metrics`) if enabled

### Success Criteria
- Define max users per Fargate task size (512 CPU / 2048 MB)
- Identify the scaling ceiling where 4 tasks are insufficient
- Determine if PgBouncer/RDS Proxy is needed at current scale
- Validate auto-scaling triggers and recovery behavior

## Thundermail Performance Testing

### Baseline Metrics to Establish
- [ ] SMTP inbound delivery latency (message received → stored)
- [ ] IMAP/JMAP fetch latency under concurrent connections
- [ ] Max concurrent IMAP connections per node
- [ ] PostgreSQL (Neon) query latency under write-heavy mail ingestion
- [ ] S3 blob store throughput for large attachments

### Load Scenarios
- [ ] Sustained inbound SMTP: N messages/second for 1 hour
- [ ] Bulk send: 10,000 messages in 5 minutes (marketing blast simulation)
- [ ] Concurrent IMAP: 1,000+ simultaneous IMAP connections
- [ ] Large attachment storm: 25 MB attachments at sustained rate
- [ ] Node failure: kill one mail node under load, verify NLB failover

### Tooling
- [smtp-source](http://www.postfix.org/smtp-source.1.html) or [swaks](https://www.jetmore.org/john/code/swaks/) for SMTP load
- [imapperf](https://github.com/UvA-FNWI/imapperf) or custom k6 script for IMAP load
- Neon PostgreSQL monitoring dashboard
- CloudWatch metrics for EC2, NLB, ElastiCache

### Success Criteria
