=== #34 [HIGH] Unrestricted egress SGs on all ECS services (accounts)
## Finding

All ECS services (accounts, Keycloak, Celery) allow egress on TCP 0-65535 to 0.0.0.0/0. A compromised container can exfiltrate data to any destination on any port.

**Severity:** HIGH
**Location:** pulumi/config.prod.yaml in [thunderbird/thunderbird-accounts](https://github.com/thunderbird/thunderbird-accounts)

## Remediation

- [ ] Restrict egress to specific destinations and ports:
  - TCP 443 to Keycloak ALB, Stalwart private NLB, Paddle API, Sentry, ECR, S3
  - TCP 5432 to PostgreSQL RDS endpoints
  - TCP 6379 to ElastiCache Redis
  - TCP 443 to VPC endpoints (Secrets Manager, ECR, CloudWatch Logs)
- [ ] Test all service integrations after restricting egress
- [ ] Document any additional egress requirements

## Notes

This is the same pattern as the mailstrom egress issue (#18). Consider a shared approach to egress restriction across all Thunderbird services.

## References

- [Security Posture Review](docs/accounts-keycloak-architecture.md#high-unrestricted-egress)

=== #33 [HIGH] No rate limiting on any API endpoint
## Finding

There is no rate limiting configured anywhere in the accounts service — not in Django REST Framework throttling, not in the ALB, and not at the application layer. All endpoints are vulnerable to:

