- [Security Posture Review](docs/accounts-keycloak-architecture.md#high-refresh-tokens-not-revoked)

=== #31 [HIGH] OIDC fallback email matching enabled in production
## Finding

Production has OIDC_FALLBACK_MATCH_BY_EMAIL set to True. If the primary OIDC ID match fails, the system falls back to matching users by email address. If an attacker can register a Keycloak account with a target's email (through race conditions or realm misconfiguration), they could take over the existing Django user account.

**Severity:** HIGH
**Location:** pulumi/config.prod.yaml in [thunderbird/thunderbird-accounts](https://github.com/thunderbird/thunderbird-accounts)

## Remediation

- [ ] Set OIDC_FALLBACK_MATCH_BY_EMAIL=False in production config
- [ ] Verify all existing users have a valid oidc_id set (no orphaned accounts that rely on email matching)
- [ ] If any users lack oidc_id, backfill from Keycloak before disabling fallback

## References

- [Security Posture Review](docs/accounts-keycloak-architecture.md#high-oidc-fallback-email-matching)

=== #30 [CRITICAL] SSL verification disabled for Stalwart API in production
## Finding

Production config sets VERIFY_PRIVATE_LINK_SSL to False for the Stalwart Management API connection. The accounts service does not verify TLS certificates when calling the Stalwart API over the VPC peering link. A man-in-the-middle on the internal network could intercept all mail provisioning operations, including creating accounts and reading mailbox metadata.

**Severity:** CRITICAL
**Location:** pulumi/config.prod.yaml in [thunderbird/thunderbird-accounts](https://github.com/thunderbird/thunderbird-accounts)

## Impact

All communication between the accounts service and Stalwart management API (account creation, quota updates, alias management, domain verification) is vulnerable to interception or modification by any host on the VPC peering path.

## Remediation

- [ ] Set VERIFY_PRIVATE_LINK_SSL=True in config.prod.yaml
- [ ] Ensure the Stalwart management endpoint presents a valid certificate
- [ ] If the private NLB uses a self-signed cert, provision an ACM certificate or install the internal CA cert in the accounts container trust store
- [ ] Test mail provisioning operations after enabling verification

## References

- [Security Posture Review](docs/accounts-keycloak-architecture.md#critical-ssl-verification-disabled-for-internal-apis)

=== #29 [CRITICAL] Keycloak brute force protection is disabled
## Finding

The `tbpro` Keycloak realm has `bruteForceProtected: false`. There is no account lockout after failed login attempts. An attacker can make unlimited password guesses against any account.

Even if brute force protection were enabled, the `failureFactor` is set to 30 — meaning 30 failed attempts before lockout, which is far too high.

**Severity:** CRITICAL
**Location:** `keycloak/data/import/tbpro-realm.json` in [thunderbird/thunderbird-accounts](https://github.com/thunderbird/thunderbird-accounts)

## Impact

Credential stuffing and brute force attacks against any Thunderbird Pro account are completely unthrottled. An attacker with a leaked email list can attempt millions of password combinations.

## Remediation

- [ ] Enable brute force protection in the `tbpro` realm (`bruteForceProtected: true`)
- [ ] Reduce `failureFactor` from 30 to 5-10
- [ ] Set `permanentLockout: false` with a reasonable `waitIncrementSeconds` (e.g., 60s)
- [ ] Configure `maxFailureWaitSeconds` (e.g., 900s / 15 minutes)
- [ ] Consider CAPTCHA integration after 3-5 failures
- [ ] Verify changes in staging before applying to production realm

## References

- [Security Posture Review](docs/accounts-keycloak-architecture.md#critical-keycloak-brute-force-protection-disabled)

