- [Security Posture Review](../docs/thundermail-architecture.md#high-no-s3-vpc-gateway-endpoint)

=== #20 [HIGH] IMDSv2 token TTL set to 6 hours
## Finding

The bootstrap script requests IMDSv2 tokens with a TTL of 21600 seconds (6 hours). The standard recommendation is ~900 seconds (15 minutes). A longer-lived token increases the window of exposure if the token is leaked.

**Severity:** HIGH
**Location:** `bootstrap/bootstrap.py` in [thunderbird/mailstrom](https://github.com/thunderbird/mailstrom)

## Remediation

- [ ] Reduce IMDSv2 token TTL from 21600s to 900s (15 minutes)
- [ ] Verify bootstrap completes well within the reduced TTL window

## References

- [Security Posture Review](../docs/thundermail-architecture.md#findings-summary)

=== #19 [HIGH] Secrets persisted in plaintext on disk
## Finding

The Phase 2 bootstrap renders secrets (database passwords, admin password, Keycloak credentials) directly into `/opt/stalwart/etc/config.toml`. This file persists on the EBS volume in plaintext. The bootstrap script does not explicitly set file permissions — the file inherits whatever the default umask produces.

If a node's EBS volume is snapshotted, shared, or the instance is compromised via SSH, all secrets are immediately exposed.

**Severity:** HIGH
**Location:** `bootstrap/bootstrap.py` in [thunderbird/mailstrom](https://github.com/thunderbird/mailstrom)

## Remediation

- [ ] Set file permissions to `0600` owned by root in `bootstrap.py` after writing config files
- [ ] Enable EBS volume encryption on all Stalwart node instances
- [ ] Investigate whether Stalwart supports fetching secrets from an external source at runtime (environment variables, Secrets Manager SDK) rather than config-file injection

## References

- [Security Posture Review](../docs/thundermail-architecture.md#high-secrets-persisted-in-plaintext-on-disk)

=== #18 [HIGH] Unrestricted egress security group rules (0–65535 to 0.0.0.0/0)
## Finding

Both the NLB security groups and EC2 node security groups allow egress on TCP ports 0–65535 to 0.0.0.0/0. While outbound connectivity is necessary for mail delivery and pulling Docker images, this is far broader than needed. A compromised node could exfiltrate data to any destination on any port.

**Severity:** HIGH
**Location:** `stalwart/__init__.py` in [thunderbird/mailstrom](https://github.com/thunderbird/mailstrom)

## Remediation

- [ ] Restrict egress to only required destinations and ports:
  - TCP 25, 465, 587 to 0.0.0.0/0 (outbound SMTP)
  - TCP 443 to 0.0.0.0/0 (Docker Hub, ACME, Keycloak)
  - TCP 5432 to Neon IP ranges (PostgreSQL)
  - TCP 6379 to Redis SG (ElastiCache)
  - TCP 443 to S3 VPC endpoint (blob storage)
- [ ] Test that Stalwart operations work correctly with restricted egress
- [ ] Document any additional egress requirements discovered during testing

## References

- [Security Posture Review](../docs/thundermail-architecture.md#high-unrestricted-egress-rules)

=== #17 [CRITICAL] PostgreSQL TLS allows invalid certificates
## Finding

The Stalwart config template accepts a `tls.allow-invalid-certs` parameter from the secrets backend. If set to `true`, connections to the PostgreSQL database (Neon) are vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks. All user mail metadata, account data, and FTS indexes transit this connection.

**Severity:** CRITICAL
**Location:** `bootstrap/templates/stalwart.toml.j2` in [thunderbird/mailstrom](https://github.com/thunderbird/mailstrom)

## Remediation

- [ ] Audit the `stalwart.postboot.postgresql_backend` secret in all environments — ensure `allow-invalid-certs` is `false`
- [ ] Consider pinning the Neon CA certificate
- [ ] Add a validation check in `bootstrap.py` that fails if `allow-invalid-certs` is `true` in production

## References

- [Security Posture Review](../docs/thundermail-architecture.md#critical-postgresql-tls-certificate-validation)

=== #16 [CRITICAL] S3 IAM policy grants s3:* — overly permissive
## Finding

The instance role's S3 policy grants `s3:*` on the blob storage bucket. This gives every Stalwart node permission to perform any S3 action, including `DeleteBucket`, `PutBucketPolicy`, `PutBucketAcl`, and `ListAllMyBuckets`. A compromised node could delete the entire bucket or make it publicly accessible.

Additionally, the resource ARN pattern uses `f'{bucket_arn}*'` instead of `f'{bucket_arn}/*'`, which could match unintended resources sharing the same ARN prefix.

**Severity:** CRITICAL
**Location:** `stalwart/s3.py` in [thunderbird/mailstrom](https://github.com/thunderbird/mailstrom)

## Remediation

- [ ] Restrict IAM actions to `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `s3:DeleteObject`, and `s3:ListBucket`
- [ ] Fix the resource ARN wildcard from `{bucket_arn}*` to `{bucket_arn}/*`
- [ ] Verify Stalwart doesn't require any other S3 actions at runtime

## References

- [Security Posture Review](../docs/thundermail-architecture.md#critical-overly-permissive-s3-iam-policy)

=== #15 [CRITICAL] Redis connections are unencrypted
## Finding

The ElastiCache Redis cluster is connected via `redis://...#insecure`, which explicitly disables TLS. All data transiting between Stalwart nodes and Redis — including pubsub coordination messages, cached session state, rate-limit counters, and spam filter data — travels in cleartext within the VPC.

Redis also appears to have no AUTH token configured, meaning any host that can reach the Redis port can read/write all data.

**Severity:** CRITICAL
**Location:** `stalwart/redis.py` in [thunderbird/mailstrom](https://github.com/thunderbird/mailstrom)

## Impact

An attacker with access to any host in the VPC (or a compromised peered VPC) could passively sniff all Redis traffic. Without AUTH, any host that can reach the Redis port can read/write all cached data, inject pubsub messages, and manipulate rate-limit state.

## Remediation

- [ ] Enable `transit_encryption_enabled` on the ElastiCache cluster
- [ ] Enable `at_rest_encryption_enabled` on the ElastiCache cluster
- [ ] Switch connection strings from `redis://` to `rediss://` (TLS)
- [ ] Remove the `#insecure` flag from connection strings
- [ ] Configure an AUTH token and pass it via Secrets Manager
- [ ] Update `stalwart.toml.j2` to use the AUTH token in Redis connection strings

## References

- [Security Posture Review](../docs/thundermail-architecture.md#critical-redis-connections-are-unencrypted)

=== #14 [Epic] AWS Security Posture & Identity Center Migration
